And then lastly, kind of talked about this one already,

482
00:21:25,428 --> 00:21:28,849
if we just spent more time going to Comic Con,

483
00:21:28,969 --> 00:21:32,910
spent more time going to whatever, all the other kind of core shows,

484
00:21:33,270 --> 00:21:36,671
we would have done a lot better not reaching out to the FGC directly.

485
00:21:36,731 --> 00:21:37,851
That's more specifically for Divekick.

486
00:21:40,251 --> 00:21:45,313
So kind of wrapping up here, there's two slides of learnings.

487
00:21:46,713 --> 00:21:47,914
Ted talked this first one already.

488
00:21:48,054 --> 00:21:49,914
People like very specific things about the games they play.

489
00:21:51,455 --> 00:21:54,456
It's interesting, like, think about it like this.

490
00:21:54,496 --> 00:21:58,717
Like, what is on your game bookshelf that you play, right?

491
00:21:59,237 --> 00:22:01,538
And if you think about what you like about all the games on your bookshelf.

492
00:22:02,711 --> 00:22:04,412
You'll notice trends, you'll notice things like that.

493
00:22:04,752 --> 00:22:06,033
And it's really easy to look at Steam

494
00:22:06,053 --> 00:22:07,454
and figure out what games people are playing

495
00:22:07,894 --> 00:22:09,916
and figure out, should I even bother trying to market it

496
00:22:09,976 --> 00:22:10,896
to this group or this group?

497
00:22:11,257 --> 00:22:12,598
Find people that like this game.

498
00:22:12,618 --> 00:22:15,039
Does that make sense to try to market to people that like?

499
00:22:17,199 --> 00:22:18,920
samurai gun or whatever it is, right?

500
00:22:19,241 --> 00:22:20,942
That's really easy to do with Steam and Steam Spy.

501
00:22:22,283 --> 00:22:23,805
Make a minimum viable product.

502
00:22:24,565 --> 00:22:26,087
This is really, I mean, you can only do this

503
00:22:26,147 --> 00:22:28,209
if the game allows it, but like I said with Divekick,

504
00:22:28,309 --> 00:22:31,251
if we would've launched with eight characters

505
00:22:31,992 --> 00:22:34,314
and put the other five out over the following six months,

506
00:22:34,674 --> 00:22:35,935
our sales curve would've been longer,

507
00:22:36,236 --> 00:22:37,317
we would've made a lot more money,

508
00:22:37,577 --> 00:22:38,838
we would've had higher engagement,

509
00:22:39,519 --> 00:22:41,100
and all those things are really good

510
00:22:41,300 --> 00:22:43,542
for commercializing these things as products, right?

511
00:22:44,989 --> 00:22:46,852
Have a plan to extend the game if it finds an audience.

512
00:22:47,253 --> 00:22:49,336
This one is, it's hard,

513
00:22:49,396 --> 00:22:50,778
this is about finding a balance, right?

514
00:22:51,119 --> 00:22:53,302
Because plans are cheap and building things are expensive.

515
00:22:54,085 --> 00:22:57,648
Right? But if you don't have enough stuff, people will never buy it because the

516
00:22:57,688 --> 00:23:02,212
value propositions off and factor into the MVP discussion. How do you do it?

517
00:23:02,252 --> 00:23:05,915
So like these two things are kind of like very coupled together in my mind.

518
00:23:06,355 --> 00:23:08,397
You can only ship an MVP. If you have plans,

519
00:23:08,417 --> 00:23:11,920
you can easily execute on to make more stuff later, right?

520
00:23:12,000 --> 00:23:15,483
And follow up with it if it finds an audience. Right. Um, and then finally,

521
00:23:15,523 --> 00:23:19,966
hype just can't be created. This is like, you know, again, this is us thinking,

522
00:23:20,227 --> 00:23:23,049
Oh, we made the hype for dive kick, not dive kick, made the hype for dive kick.

523
00:23:24,239 --> 00:23:28,601
And it's an easy mistake to fall into with success,

524
00:23:28,661 --> 00:23:30,642
to think like, oh yeah, this was good because of us.

525
00:23:30,702 --> 00:23:32,063
And it's really, no, it's the game.

526
00:23:32,143 --> 00:23:32,783
It's always the game.

527
00:23:37,994 --> 00:23:40,115
Yeah, so whatever your original business plan is,

528
00:23:41,056 --> 00:23:42,297
like it would have been really easy

529
00:23:42,718 --> 00:23:44,379
to keep pouring money into GunSport,

530
00:23:44,800 --> 00:23:46,321
to keep pouring money into CapsuleForce,

531
00:23:46,341 --> 00:23:47,762
to keep pouring money into VideoBall,

532
00:23:48,403 --> 00:23:50,585
but I don't think we would have gotten a better result.

533
00:23:50,925 --> 00:23:53,848
Like VideoBall, GunSport, CapsuleForce,

534
00:23:54,388 --> 00:23:56,130
the market is so much more competitive now

535
00:23:56,730 --> 00:23:58,332
than when it was when we launched DiveKick in 2013, right?

536
00:23:59,933 --> 00:24:01,935
And I don't think you can do small-scale publishing

537
00:24:02,455 --> 00:24:04,717
on the budgets we were talking about in this day and age.

538
00:24:04,737 --> 00:24:05,878
I just don't think it works, right?

539
00:24:07,319 --> 00:24:09,020
And so pouring more money still would have been

540
00:24:09,040 --> 00:24:10,862
just a little bit of money in the grand scheme of things.

541
00:24:11,102 --> 00:24:13,704
Like, you know, these aren't like $2 million video games, right?

542
00:24:14,304 --> 00:24:16,446
So I think one of the things we did right

543
00:24:16,466 --> 00:24:17,547
from an Iron Galaxy perspective,

544
00:24:17,567 --> 00:24:20,609
it was very painful to have that conversation with Brandon

545
00:24:20,850 --> 00:24:21,510
and explain to him.

546
00:24:21,951 --> 00:24:24,913
that we're walking away from GunSport and he can have it back.

547
00:24:25,773 --> 00:24:28,535
But from Iron Galaxy's perspective it was absolutely the very right thing to do

548
00:24:28,555 --> 00:24:31,358
because it just wasn't going to end well.

549
00:24:31,778 --> 00:24:33,419
VideoBall wouldn't have ended as well

550
00:24:33,979 --> 00:24:35,901
and we had to kind of pick our battles there.

551
00:24:37,122 --> 00:24:39,924
This is a good one. I think this is...

552
00:24:40,885 --> 00:24:42,206
If you're doing streams and getting 44 viewers...

553
00:24:43,728 --> 00:25:04,026
If you're going to shows and not getting a buzz, you know, if you're doing trailers and they get 10 YouTube views on YouTube the first day, you need to think about what the fuck you're doing. You're doing something wrong, right? Either something's wrong with the game. Something is wrong with your approach. Something is wrong with your outreach. You're doing something wrong, and you need to reevaluate even doing it at all, right?

554
00:25:06,989 --> 00:25:09,572
Good job. That's me.

555
00:25:10,353 --> 00:25:11,955
Don't artificially limit your potential audience.

556
00:25:12,035 --> 00:25:14,758
This is a mistake we made on Divekick. I kind of already talked about it.

557
00:25:15,199 --> 00:25:20,305
We just leaned so hard into FGC stuff and had kind of a rough edge around everything we did with Divekick.

558
00:25:20,325 --> 00:25:22,087
I'm sure it turned away potential consumers.

559
00:25:23,489 --> 00:25:26,132
In fact, consumers that were the people that ended up buying the game.

560
00:25:27,218 --> 00:25:30,881
Finally, if you're working as a publisher, you have external dev teams, probably.

561
00:25:31,482 --> 00:25:33,644
Don't assume anything about the external dev teams.

562
00:25:33,684 --> 00:25:38,488
One of the bigger mistakes we made was, okay, we shipped, I think Iron Galaxy at this point

563
00:25:38,548 --> 00:25:42,572
has shipped or helped shipped over 100 products in eight and a half years.

564
00:25:42,632 --> 00:25:43,453
No one's done that.

565
00:25:43,553 --> 00:25:43,713
Right?

566
00:25:44,474 --> 00:25:46,115
and you get really good by shipping things.

567
00:25:46,575 --> 00:25:48,636
And these teams we work with are all very capable teams,

568
00:25:49,016 --> 00:25:50,617
but they just don't have that much experience, right?

569
00:25:51,278 --> 00:25:52,898
And so we did not ask,

570
00:25:52,938 --> 00:25:55,040
we asked them questions we would ask ourselves.

571
00:25:55,660 --> 00:25:57,621
We didn't ask them questions that you would have,

572
00:25:57,661 --> 00:25:59,803
you should have been asking us eight and a half years ago.

573
00:26:00,903 --> 00:26:02,604
And so I think we should have been more proactive

574
00:26:02,644 --> 00:26:03,405
about a lot of things.

575
00:26:03,908 --> 00:26:05,269
I think we should have been more involved.

576
00:26:05,730 --> 00:26:07,571
They all would have hated every second of it, right?

577
00:26:07,991 --> 00:26:09,452
But I'm sure it would have been better

578
00:26:09,492 --> 00:26:11,233
if we were more involved in every kind of,

579
00:26:12,093 --> 00:26:13,955
even creative decisions and just talking stuff out.

