00:26:33,778 --> 00:26:34,639
I was kind of hoping to hear more

585
00:26:34,660 --> 00:26:35,781
about your conference strategy.

586
00:26:35,801 --> 00:26:37,544
Was that purely for like player acquisition

587
00:26:37,564 --> 00:26:38,526
or were you doing other stuff?

588
00:26:39,047 --> 00:26:41,030
And when you talk about big shows like Comic-Con,

589
00:26:41,692 --> 00:26:43,034
being a smaller company, do you ever fear

590
00:26:43,054 --> 00:26:44,376
about getting like drowned out next

591
00:26:44,436 --> 00:26:45,558
like the Avengers or something?

592
00:26:45,981 --> 00:26:48,043
Yeah, so the question was, he wants to know,

593
00:26:49,044 --> 00:26:50,005
what's our show strategy?

594
00:26:50,046 --> 00:26:53,369
What do we try to get out of showing things like PAX?

595
00:26:53,950 --> 00:26:55,792
And are bigger shows worth it for a smaller team?

596
00:26:56,272 --> 00:26:58,895
Yeah, it's strictly about acquisition and user engagement.

597
00:26:59,556 --> 00:27:01,278
You can try to set press stuff up at shows,

598
00:27:01,298 --> 00:27:02,179
but they never come.

599
00:27:02,920 --> 00:27:03,660
It's really challenging.

600
00:27:05,923 --> 00:27:08,345
The other thing that's really great about shows is as a developer,

